{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L1m4Qmakh8BbFwWL5Y4Xsc","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# iam\n2\t\n3\tPurpose: Identity and access management service for the platform. Exposes user lifecycle (registration, authentication) and RBAC authorisation over HTTP on port 8082.\n4\tTags: architecture, design\n5\t\n6\t## File Index\n7\t\n8\t| File | Description |\n9\t|------|-------------|\n10\t| `iam.go` | Package entry point; `New()` wires sub-components and returns `http.Handler` |\n11\t| `lifecycle/lifecycle.go` | In-memory user store and token session management; registers `/users` and `/auth` routes |\n12\t| `authz/authz.go` | In-memory role store and user-role assignments; registers `/roles`, `/users/{id}/roles`, and `/authz/check` routes |\n13\t\n14\t## Overview\n15\t\n16\tThe `iam` package is an internal composite composed of two atomic sub-packages:\n17\t\n18\t- **lifecycle** — owns user CRUD and auth tokens. Users are stored in a `map[string]User` keyed by UUID. Passwords are stored as bcrypt hashes. Login issues an opaque token (UUID); logout invalidates it. All state is guarded by a `sync.RWMutex`.\n19\t\n20\t- **authz** — owns RBAC. Roles have a name and a set of permission strings. Users can be assigned multiple roles. `POST /authz/check` resolves whether a user has a given permission by walking their assigned roles. State is in-memory with its own mutex. Role IDs assigned as UUIDs. User IDs are opaque strings (no direct import of lifecycle — loose coupling via string IDs).\n21\t\n22\t- **integrate** (`iam.go`) — instantiates both sub-packages, registers all routes on a single `http.ServeMux`, and returns the mux as `http.Handler`. The top-level `main.go` binds this handler to `:8082`.\n23\t\n24\t### Route Summary\n25\t\n26\t| Method | Path | Handler |\n27\t|--------|------|---------|\n28\t| POST | /users | lifecycle |\n29\t| GET | /users/{id} | lifecycle |\n30\t| DELETE | /users/{id} | lifecycle |\n31\t| POST | /auth/login | lifecycle |\n32\t| POST | /auth/logout | lifecycle |\n33\t| POST | /roles | authz |\n34\t| GET | /roles | authz |\n35\t| POST | /users/{id}/roles | authz |\n36\t| GET | /users/{id}/roles | authz |\n37\t| POST | /authz/check | authz |\n38\t\n39\t### Design Constraints\n40\t\n41\t- No external database; all state lives in process memory.\n42\t- Go module: `github.com/cornjacket/platform`; packages at `internal/iam`, `internal/iam/lifecycle`, `internal/iam/authz`.\n43\t- The `integrate` component does not add a subdirectory — `iam.go` lives directly in the output directory alongside the sub-package directories.\n44\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4c80310d-fe03-450c-af20-b455d8b45e9d","uuid":"ae66d2be-1912-4829-b1db-1d2fea51a51a","timestamp":"2026-04-05T22:28:14.684Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/david/Go/src/github.com/cornjacket/ai-builder/establish-regression-recordings/sandbox/regressions/doc-platform-monolith/output/internal/iam/README.md","content":"# iam\n\nPurpose: Identity and access management service for the platform. Exposes user lifecycle (registration, authentication) and RBAC authorisation over HTTP on port 8082.\nTags: architecture, design\n\n## File Index\n\n| File | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `iam.go` | Package entry point; `New()` wires sub-components and returns `http.Handler` |\n| `lifecycle/lifecycle.go` | In-memory user store and token session management; registers `/users` and `/auth` routes |\n| `authz/authz.go` | In-memory role store and user-role assignments; registers `/roles`, `/users/{id}/roles`, and `/authz/check` routes |\n\n## Overview\n\nThe `iam` package is an internal composite composed of two atomic sub-packages:\n\n- **lifecycle** — owns user CRUD and auth tokens. Users are stored in a `map[string]User` keyed by UUID. Passwords are stored as bcrypt hashes. Login issues an opaque token (UUID); logout invalidates it. All state is guarded by a `sync.RWMutex`.\n\n- **authz** — owns RBAC. Roles have a name and a set of permission strings. Users can be assigned multiple roles. `POST /authz/check` resolves whether a user has a given permission by walking their assigned roles. State is in-memory with its own mutex. Role IDs assigned as UUIDs. User IDs are opaque strings (no direct import of lifecycle — loose coupling via string IDs).\n\n- **integrate** (`iam.go`) — instantiates both sub-packages, registers all routes on a single `http.ServeMux`, and returns the mux as `http.Handler`. The top-level `main.go` binds this handler to `:8082`.\n\n### Route Summary\n\n| Method | Path | Handler |\n|--------|------|---------|\n| POST | /users | lifecycle |\n| GET | /users/{id} | lifecycle |\n| DELETE | /users/{id} | lifecycle |\n| POST | /auth/login | lifecycle |\n| POST | /auth/logout | lifecycle |\n| POST | /roles | authz |\n| GET | /roles | authz |\n| POST | /users/{id}/roles | authz |\n| GET | /users/{id}/roles | authz |\n| POST | /authz/check | authz |\n\n### Design Constraints\n\n- No external database; all state lives in process memory.\n- Go module: `github.com/cornjacket/platform`; packages at `internal/iam`, `internal/iam/lifecycle`, `internal/iam/authz`.\n- The `integrate` component does not add a subdirectory — `iam.go` lives directly in the output directory alongside the sub-package directories.\n","numLines":44,"startLine":1,"totalLines":44}}}
